Part 1: Water Column Characteristics



Plot showing with daily flow rate and the nitrate concentration/flux across the study period. Horizonal bars show the sample dates.
Here I created an additional figure to look at all the water column data. I omitted the samples that were taken at odd locations (7.1, 6b, 5b etc).




Next, I divided the data into seasons for comparison of water column characteristics. This allows us to boost sample numbers and generate estimates of variance.

Winter = Dec, Jan, Feb
Spring = March, Apr, May
Summer = June, July, Aug
Fall = Sept, Oct, Nov

Separating out the individual variables for closer inspection and statistics.

Part 2: Suspended Sediment Characteristics



In this part of the analysis we look at isotope values for suspended sediments at each location sampled in the estuary. I conducted a couple of ANCOVA models to test for differences among year, season and site for each isotope. I have also created a matrix plot that looks at all the individual values for each year x site x season combination. In general, it is clear that the more samples become more enriched in del 13C and del 15N as we move down river. This might not the best way to present this but a good first stab.

c.mod<-aov(dat.temp2$del_13C~dat.temp2$Station_alt+dat.temp2$Season+dat.temp2$Year)
summary(c.mod)

To match this plot I conducted a cluster analysis to see if there are statistical groupings by the isotope values. This is multivariate analysis that takes into account both the C and N values together.

Based on the cluster, it looks like 3 strong groups along the estuarine gradient.
Lower estuary: sites 0-4
Middle estuary: sites 5-6
Upper estuary: sites 7-10

Additional Isotope visualizations



Next, I plotting the data a difference way, using barplots that looks at c and N separately. This might be the better way to present this data for this paper.

The mean N15 enrichment of zooplankton relative to water col = 3.358371 +- 1.6895031

The mean C13 enrichment of zooplankton relative to water col 1.7289152 +- 3.0589326

The difference in the isotope values at each location suggests that zooplankton are secondary consumers feeding on primary producers at each site.
